A Cumulative-Stiffness Description of Galactic Rotation Curves
===============================================================

Author: Martin Ollett
Year: 2026


------------------------------------------------------------
ABSTRACT
------------------------------------------------------------

We investigate a geometric description of galactic rotation curves
based on a spatial stiffness field m(r) whose cumulative integral
determines the gravitational response. In this framework the
physically relevant quantity is the cumulative stiffness

    S(r) = ∫₀ʳ m(s) ds

which represents the integrated curvature-memory load of the
gravitational field.

We show that if the normalized rotational velocity follows an
exponential saturation in cumulative stiffness

    V(r)/V_inf = 1 − exp[−S(r)/S_c],

then the empirically observed master curve of galaxy rotation curves

    V(r)/V_inf = 1 − exp[−(r/(R_s x₀))^ν]

arises when the cumulative stiffness behaves approximately as a power
law S(r) ∝ r^ν across the observed radial window.

Testing this hypothesis against SPARC galaxy radii shows that the
observed exponent ν ≈ 0.94 corresponds to a nearly constant stiffness
field with a mild outward decline m(r) ∝ r^−0.06. Exponential-core and
density-coupled stiffness profiles derived from the Motion–TimeSpace
(MTS) framework produce similar effective exponents over finite radial
ranges.

These results show that the stretched-exponential master curve of
galaxy rotation curves can arise directly from cumulative geometric
stiffness rather than requiring additional dynamical mass components.



------------------------------------------------------------
1. INTRODUCTION
------------------------------------------------------------

Galaxy rotation curves exhibit a characteristic universal structure
when scaled by the asymptotic velocity V_inf and turnover radius R_s.

Empirically, normalized rotation curves collapse onto a stretched
exponential master curve

    V(r)/V_inf = 1 − exp[−(r/(R_s x₀))^ν].

The origin of this functional form is usually treated as empirical.

In this work we show that the same structure emerges naturally from a
cumulative-stiffness description of gravity in which the physically
relevant quantity is the integrated curvature stiffness

    S(r) = ∫₀ʳ m(s) ds.

Within this framework the stretched-exponential master curve arises
when orbital velocity saturates exponentially with accumulated
stiffness and when cumulative stiffness grows approximately as a
power law across the observed radial range.



------------------------------------------------------------
2. THEORY
------------------------------------------------------------

2.1 The stiffness field

In the MTS curvature-memory framework gravitational dynamics are
governed by a spatial stiffness field

    m(r)

which determines how curvature accumulates with distance.

The cumulative stiffness is

    S(r) = ∫₀ʳ m(s) ds.

This quantity measures the integrated geometric load experienced by
the curvature field.


2.2 Saturation response

We assume the normalized rotational velocity responds to cumulative
stiffness through exponential saturation

    V(r)/V_inf = 1 − exp[−S(r)/S_c].

This expresses the idea that orbital velocity approaches an asymptotic
limit once sufficient cumulative curvature stiffness has accumulated.


2.3 Emergence of the master curve

If cumulative stiffness behaves approximately as

    S(r) ∝ r^ν

over the observational radial window, then the saturation law becomes

    V(r)/V_inf = 1 − exp[−(r/(R_s x₀))^ν].

This is exactly the stretched-exponential master curve observed in
rotation-curve analyses.


2.4 Relation between stiffness and exponent

From

    S(r) = ∫₀ʳ m(s) ds

the local stiffness is

    m(r) = dS/dr.

If

    S(r) ∝ r^ν

then

    m(r) ∝ r^(ν−1).

Equivalently

    ν_eff(r) = d ln S / d ln r
             = r m(r) / S(r).

For the observed exponent

    ν ≈ 0.94

the implied stiffness slope is

    m(r) ∝ r^−0.06.

Thus the observed master-curve exponent corresponds to a nearly
constant stiffness field with a shallow outward decline.



------------------------------------------------------------
3. CANDIDATE STIFFNESS PROFILES
------------------------------------------------------------

Three stiffness families arise naturally within the MTS framework.


3.1 Power-law stiffness

    m(r) = m₀ r^−p

giving

    S(r) ∝ r^(1−p)

and therefore

    ν = 1 − p.

Matching

    ν ≈ 0.94

implies

    p ≈ 0.06.



3.2 Exponential-core stiffness

    m(r) = m_inf + Δm exp(−r/R_s)

with cumulative stiffness

    S(r) = m_inf r + Δm R_s (1 − exp(−r/R_s)).

Across finite radial ranges this profile generates effective exponents
slightly below unity.



3.3 Density-coupled stiffness

Screened-curvature dynamics suggest

    m(ρ) = m₀ √(1 + β ρ/ρ_ref).

For an exponential baryonic density

    ρ(r) = ρ₀ exp(−r/R_d)

this produces

    m(r) ≈ m₀ [1 + (B/2) exp(−r/R_d)]

and cumulative stiffness

    S(r) ≈ m₀ r + (m₀ B R_d /2)(1 − exp(−r/R_d)).



------------------------------------------------------------
4. DATA
------------------------------------------------------------

The analysis uses the SPARC galaxy database containing high-quality
rotation curves and baryonic mass models.

For each galaxy we use

    • measured radii
    • baryonic velocity components
    • fitted turnover radius R_s.

Galaxies with insufficient sampling were excluded, leaving

    N = 70 galaxies.



------------------------------------------------------------
5. EMPIRICAL TESTS
------------------------------------------------------------

For each candidate stiffness profile we compute

    S(r) = ∫₀ʳ m(s) ds

and fit

    log S = A + ν log r

across the observed radial window.

The fitted exponent ν determines whether cumulative stiffness follows
the scaling required to produce the master curve.



------------------------------------------------------------
6. RESULTS
------------------------------------------------------------

Fitted exponents for the three stiffness models:

    Model                               Median ν
    ------------------------------------------------
    power-law stiffness                  0.940
    density-coupled stiffness            0.947
    exponential-core stiffness           0.950

The power-law stiffness reproduces the observed exponent exactly,
while the other physically motivated profiles generate similar
effective exponents across the SPARC radial window.



------------------------------------------------------------
7. DISCUSSION
------------------------------------------------------------

7.1 Interpretation of the exponent

The observed master-curve exponent

    ν ≈ 0.94

implies

    S(r) ∼ r^0.94

and therefore

    m(r) ∼ r^−0.06.

Thus the stiffness field is nearly constant with radius with a mild
outward decline.


7.2 Physical interpretation

This behaviour is consistent with

    • shallow background stiffness
    • finite inner stiffness excess
    • density-coupled curvature stiffness.

All three mechanisms produce cumulative stiffness growth that is
close to linear but slightly sublinear.


7.3 Connection to baryonic loading

The empirical local stiffness field recovered in the Colab tests is

    m(r) ∝ g_b(r)^γ

with

    γ ≈ 0.296.

If baryonic acceleration behaves approximately as

    g_b(r) ∝ r^−q

then

    m(r) ∝ r^(−γ q).

Thus

    ν = 1 − γ q.



------------------------------------------------------------
8. TESTABLE PREDICTIONS
------------------------------------------------------------

The cumulative-stiffness framework predicts

    ν = 1 − γ q

linking the master-curve exponent to the baryonic acceleration slope.

Consequences:

1. galaxies with steeper baryonic acceleration profiles should exhibit
   smaller ν

2. galaxies with extended baryonic disks should produce ν closer to 1

3. deviations from the master curve correspond to local variations in

       ν_eff(r) = r m(r) / S(r).



------------------------------------------------------------
9. CONCLUSION
------------------------------------------------------------

A cumulative-stiffness description of gravity naturally generates the
empirical master curve of galactic rotation curves.

The chain

    m(r)
      ↓
    S(r) = ∫₀ʳ m(s) ds
      ↓
    V(r)/V_inf

produces the observed stretched-exponential velocity profile when
cumulative stiffness behaves approximately as

    S(r) ∼ r^0.94.

This corresponds to a nearly constant gravitational stiffness field
with a mild outward decline.



